With regard to communication, there is a debate about its effectiveness in producing cooperative outcomes. In the mediation literature, some scholars have argued that information provision is an effective mediation tool (Fisher 1995; Dixon 1996). The prime role of information is reducing uncertainty. Moreover, by providing the disputants with information about each other’s reservation points, mediators may also help the disputants locate the bargaining set (Savun 2008). Other scholars have argued that information provided by mediators may not be sufficient to achieve cooperative outcomes (Morgan 1994; Bercovitch 1996; Smith and Stam 2003). This view is consistent with an understanding of communication as cheap talk (Farrell and Rabin 1996). In a social dilemma, self-interested players are expected to use communication to try to convince others to cooperate, but then choose the Nash equilibrium strategy when they make their private decisions. Thus, communication should not make a difference in the outcomes achieved in social dilemmas (at least not for the final result
1
). Understanding mediation as a form of cheap talk means that disputants will have an incentive to misrepresent their true reservation points and to “bluff” to the other side. This has also consequences for the information provided by the mediator. According to Kydd (2003, 599) “if there is an incentive to bluff to the other side, there will be an incentive to bluff to the mediator.” A conflict party will not reveal its true reservation points to the mediator since the latter will make this information public. Hence, as Smith and Stam (2003), note, there is no way for the mediator to reach an outcome that the disputants could not have reached on their own. Only if mediators have access to outside information, information provision by the mediator can be effective (Savun 2008; Fey and Ramsay 2010).
